. Here my poor
husband
paid the debt of
nature, and Jenny became the mother of a fine boy.
As
she
passed
for a widow, and was in the full bloom
of beauty, it is not to be wondered that
she
should
be
addressed
on the
score
of marriage by a young man who
kept a
persumery
and toy-
shop
in the neighbourhood.
Jenny's heart was
still
too full of the idea of
Ponsonville
to
suffer
any other attachment to grow on it; but poverty
began to
stare
us in the face:
she
saw
on one
side
, a
mother, a child pining with want, no protector, no friend
to comfort and relieve them; on the other, a home, a
protector, and a place of refuge for
those
objects
so
dear
to her heart. She acceded to his
