suppose
that inclination led me to
give my hand to that ludicrous piece of antiquity:
No, my dear girl, I married him to
serve
a father,
whom next to heaven, I love, and to get from the
power of an ill-natured old maiden aunt, who had kept
me at
school
for fear I
should
mar her fortune, and
despoil
her of all her lovers; for
she
had thirty
thousand
pounds independent fortune, and that gave her wizened
face and
skeleton
figure ten
thousand
charms;
she
or her
fortune had admirers innumerable. I was always with
her at the holidays. My Lord
saw
me at the play.
Charmed with the idea of getting me married out of the
way,
she
made her will, bequeathing to me all her
fortune
,
in
case
she
died without
issue
.
This was buzzed abouther lovers all
forsook
her
and poor aunty died of a broken heart in the fifty
ninth year of her age! My father had married this
Lady's
sister
. He was poor. She was the co-
heiress
of a
la ge fortune; but alas!
she
knew not that if
she
married
without her guardians
consent
, the whole of her
fortune
went to her
eldest
sister
.
Disappointment
and
